<subSubSection id="29EE3190C3E82BB04CA94964039F7B7B" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2DDF9CBCFC7E1D8E1688557A2CD89D41" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A0AA2C8111BDAF099B4388B7C4C8C6AF" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">
The specific epithet is an allusion to the characteristic inferior appendages, which are apically truncated. Derived from the Latin, &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="2330F826382B302AE047938DE94D4D87" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Dumas &amp; Rozo &amp; Desidério &amp; Takiya" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Chimarra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chimarra truncata" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis id="D103C771B4DE0D1C4E2C6B8EB47F8A0C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">Chimarra truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; = piece cut off, tip, end.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
